PIP: This paper examines the patterns of timing of births of women using data 
from the Canadian Fertility Survey of 1984. Simi-Markovian schemes are applied 
to the maternity histories of the 5315 sample women in their reproductive ages 
in order to measure the intensity and timing of childbearing. 
Age-and-duration-specific transition probabilities are found to have 
substantially changed for the more recent birth cohorts compared to the older 
cohorts. Clear-cut changes in intensity and timing of childbearing were 
initiated by women who are aged 30-34 at the time of survey, that is, those who 
started childbearing in the late 1960s and early 1970s. Childlessness, either 
due to physiological sterility or due to voluntary decision, is definitely 
increasing, from 8% among women who had completed their reproductive life at the 
time of survey to 15-20% among younger women. 2nd births are highly probable to 
follow 1st births promptly, even among younger cohorts. Large differences among 
cohorts are to be found either in 1st births (whose timing is increasingly 
spread out among younger cohorts) or in 3rd births (which are becoming rare). 
Younger cohorts show a trend to resort to surgical sterilization of tubal 
ligation soon after 2nd birth, with 11% of women sterilized by age 30 and 25% by 
age 35. With respect to the distributions of birth intervals, mean ages at 1st 
births center around 23 or 24 for all cohorts. For higher order births, mean 
intervals converge to 3 years for younger cohorts.. This analysis is based on 
parity states only. It seems that these patterns are the result of profound 
changes taking place in the lifestyles of women in terms of educational 
attainment, labor force participation, religious behavior and place of 
residence, and the correlates of the transition probabilities from 1 parity to 
another also require investigation.

